Hello Chris, I will address your question with two responses. I will
first discuss other work in the field and the second with a one minute
history of my own work.

As of this morning Google notes about 400K hits for value network and
value networks. Clearly it is a popular term and one is that is
growing quickly in usage. while this is not a comprehensive history of
the term I believe it will give you a quick perspective.

I have no idea where the term originally was used, but it began to
come into general usage in the late 1990s in the supply chain world, e-
commerce, customer relationship management,  and industry analysis.
There was some interest in the KM community but most of the network
thinking there is still focused on communities of practice and
knowledge networks, which are best understood with social network
analysis. The term seems to resonate with a growing interest in
understanding organizations as complex adapative systems.

There are a couple of other books on value nets (Bovet and Martha,
Cinzia Parolini) and many that include the topic either directly
(Christensen's Innovator's Dilemma) or indirectly (Iansiti and Levie,
Keystone Advantage). Stabel and Fjelstad also are known for comparing
value networks and value shops and there is an academic group in
Finland that also does work in value networks. A complementary method
was developed by Jeff Shuman and Jan Twombly that is described in
Collaborative Communities and Everyone is a Customer, but their method
is proprietary other than what lis in their books. Their includes a
similar value network mapping method and an analysis table configured
for understanding the value exchanges with customers and stakeholders.
Jeff teaches at Bentley College in the Boston area.

Most other methods seem to fall into two categories. The first is the
process view of the world where value network is a term used to refer
to complex supply chains. Such methods build on process tools, the
most common of these being value stream mapping, which is used a lot
in Lean. The Parolini value net method, which is quite solid work,
also comes from the same perspective.

The second category is a type of cluster analysis which looks at
various attributes and relationships of stakeholders in industry
clusters. Cluster analysis has been around for quite some time and is
of course complementary to value network analysis, as are all of these
other methods. Christensen's work would fall into this category I
believe and we recently saw a draft of a good critique of his work
that we hope to include on the www.value-networks.com site when it is
finalized.

Very few value network analysis methods actually use any kind of
network analysis - in the sense that they are trying to understand
dynamic relationships. That brings us to classis social network
analysis and how people in that field think about value. Mark
Granovetter and colleague have identified a number of foundational
articles in the book SocioEconomics that address the question of value
creation. I found a couple of good articles in that publication but
for the most part social network analysis has not addressed the
question of value in what I would consider a satisfactory way. There
are of course a lot of people working on that such as Rob Cross and
Validis's work on economic regions is alos noteworthy, but most of the
SNA/ONA people define value in economic or financial terms, which
misses the foundation of network relationships in non-financial or
intangible value.

We are always on the lookout for good work in this area and good
articles to include on the open resource site so if anyone has come
across something else that needs to be included please send it along.
It is not necessary to &quot;speak the party line.&quot; That Value Network
Consortium want to feature and high quality articles, practitioners
and methods  that are coming from the perspective of complex
adaptative sytems and are dynamic modeling methods.

More on my own work in another post....
Verna

http://www.vernaallee.com/value_networks/Reconfiguring_the_Value_Netw...

