<POSTER> &quot;Richard Vines&quot; &lt;pless...@netspace.net.au&gt; </POSTER>
<POSTDATE> 2007-08-11T19:37:00 </POSTDATE>
Thank you Verna for this important personal narration of your journey.
Fascinating stuff given that this description of your journey is interwoven
with an ambience of personal exploration linked to references to the &quot;out
there&quot; world of happenings in the related space of value networks.

I have a question of the group which in a sense might relate (only in part)
to Chris's question. I have been doing a bit of work / thinking in both the
corporate and third sectors recently. The driver in the first relates to the
need for integrated strategic procurement practices and ensuring the
mechanisms are in place to manage cap ex spends in more strategic ways than
in the past. The latter relates to new legislation defined by Government
intent (a State Govt, not a Federal Govt).

I am taken by the phrase in value networks - namely that you cannot direct
the network, but you can only serve it (or something like that). There is an
implied sense of &quot;power dynamics&quot; in this statement, which at base level, I
agree with. From my perspective, this is about the shift from hierarchical
control mechanisms to permeable diffuse mechanisms of influence - on the
recognition that individuals participate, knowingly or otherwise in complex
adaptive systems.

Throughout the past 12 months of reading posts on value networks, I to this
day feel there is not contained within the vernacular of value networks the
ability to reconcile the difficulties of what I call personal knowledge
embodied in the social relationships of value networks, with the objective
knowledge of large complex organizations - cutting across both corporate and
community based organizations.

In many areas of work I am currently sensing a way through, there is a need
to ensure explicit recognition is given to interacting with a formal
hierarchy. The informal and the formal need to co-exist in the vernacular of
the ontology of organisational knowledge.

In most of the semantics I read into this value network world, the focus on
narrative and intangibles leads us to a space that focuses attention
primarily at the boundaries of a different type of knowledge - the &quot;formal&quot;
organisational knowledge. And yet, in my own work, nothing will ever lead to
transforming impact of localized highly contextualized practice - if there
is not explicit attention given to the need to integrate the formal with the
informal, the personal with the collective, and the network with the
hierarchy.

Now to the question. Am I missing something about the vernacular of value
networks that can deal with my quandary? It just seems to me that in the
vernacular a large part of the notion of &quot;context&quot; is missing. And in part
this relates to the authorization process of using the value network
methodology in the first place. It seems to me that the role-link-exchange
ontology suggests we can arrive and start mapping the role-link-exchange
action context, without thinking about how it is that we become part of the
context involving the commencement of this process in the first place. It
just seems that the vernacular of value networks is not sufficiently framed
to take this into account.

Anyway, it is a question I have kept thinking about myself and through the
limited inputs I have made to this group over a period of time.

Richard

