Yes, good point Graham - although I am not sure if the informalising of
formal structures can be attributed directly to the impact of VNA?

Here in Vic, in the community sector there is a whole social language that
has developed around partnership and network governance. To me it represents
a confused position. That is the need for networked ways of delivering value
is becoming more explicitly understood. At the same time the risk management
exposure still seems to be all one way.

It seems to me that the solution has to involve new approaches to governance
- and the same is true in the corporate sector. That is, the solution is not
just embedded in an analysis of the exchange mechanisms. Part of solution
involves reaching negotiated agreements about how a system should work and
be governed in the first place. I don't have to do an exchange mapping
process to work that out.

And yet, governance is a naughty word because you can only serve a network
and not direct it. Whilst I agree with this, I only agree with it to the
extent that the ontology of organisational (and extended networked)
knowledge embraces objective and other types of knowledge, hierarchies and
networks, formal and informal flows, formal organisational structures and
cross departmental network-governance arrangements, narrative capture and
formal data analysis. Whilst this is saying the obvious, I have not sensed
that the nomenclature is explicitly inclusive of these wider approaches to
contextual influences.

It might be a silly question, but would we run a nuclear economy using VNA?
Parts of it yes. But, objective hard nosed knowledge is required as well. If
this is not explicitly recognised, the impacts are too horrendous to think
about. As I say, this might be a silly example, but it is underpinned by
some deep philosophical issues in relation to how we understand knowledge in
the first place.

By the way, I don't want my question to detract from Verna's wonderful
explanation of the history of her involvement in VNA. It is a great story
and we are all grateful for the networked effect of this work!

Richard

