I think the term network governance is an oxymoron isn't it? Yes that
is a confused position. The new approach to governance is the
sensemaking that comes with using methods like narrative and value
network analysis. I find that the conversation about context tends to
ramble in circles until people get down to the specific roles and
interactions that surface in the mapping process. Consider VNA as a
way to get at context and surface the tough issues, not something you
do instead of that.

You are assuming that an analysis of value network exchanges is far
more &quot;rational&quot; than it is. Yes patterns can be surfaced through
visualizing network interactions in a variety of ways (both manual and
automated) but the interpretation and sense making is still a very
human activity that is deeply dependent on both the tacit knowledge of
individuals and the shared understanding that can only come about
through conversation.

By the way I am not sure I have ever met truly &quot;objective' knowledge.
I assume you are referring to some kind of scientific knowledge but it
is a real stretch to assume that even scientific knowledge is by any
means objective.

Verna

