Thanks. I use the word objective here only in the sense that knowledge is
fallible and is tested in the micro niche environments in which it is
constructed in language (this is the evolutionary idea). Yes, scientific
paradigms are where this heads, but each scientific claim is only a claim
and it is only in negotiated agreements about what works that it begins to
mirror the world. I do not use the word objective from the frame that I
think you have responded from. And, I think that is at the heart of my
question.

Anyway, I am raising issues which I think have been raised before. So, I
think my question remains, but it is in the end my question. I agree with
your point about sense-making and VNA and the importance of conversation. It
is more the idea of the time value of knowledge that I am questioning.
Organisations have different sensemaking patterns going on with that relate
to a range of different types of knowledge. Formal hierarchies can embody
some types of knowledge as well as those that lie at the boundaries. All
together forms part of context.

Thanks.

I think I have said this right.
Richard

