And the question about network-governance? If the idea that organizations
are dealing with different types of knowledge (because of the different
value that accrues to those different types of knowledge over time), then I
do not necessarily think that network-governance is an oxymoron. Some
knowledge is emergent and particular for one point in time. Other types of
knowledge have moved well beyond emergence and are embedded deeply in the
social, physical, linguistic and management systems. Both co-exist and both
interact. A seedling is different to a tree, but they might be called the
same thing, if they are the same species.

Richard

