&gt;&gt;&gt; Part 2 - a bullet point history of my own work.

&gt;&gt;&gt; Mid 1970's I created a networked sign manufacturing company with my
&gt;&gt;&gt; former husband that in terms of revenue was practically one of the
&gt;&gt;&gt; largest in its industry. We had no employees, no plant, virtually no
&gt;&gt;&gt; overhead and yet we handled large chain store accounts and installed
&gt;&gt;&gt; signs from Anchorage to Florida. I learned that any organization
&gt;&gt;&gt; could
&gt;&gt;&gt; be thought of and even operated as a network.

&gt;&gt;&gt; 1980's collected various university degrees trying to understand
&gt;&gt;&gt; business and organizations as complex adaptive systems, worked in
&gt;&gt;&gt; corporate middle management for a large retail organization.

&gt;&gt;&gt; 1991 Hung out my consulting shingle focued on organizational
&gt;&gt;&gt; learnign
&gt;&gt;&gt; and systems thinking ( this was before Senge's book came out - so
&gt;&gt;&gt; nobody came)

&gt;&gt;&gt; 1992 Began supporting benchmarking activities on complex process
&gt;&gt;&gt; reengineering projects for companies like AT&amp;T, Chevron, Pacific
&gt;&gt;&gt; Bell,
&gt;&gt;&gt; many others. (Sneaking in collaborative learning and systems
&gt;&gt;&gt; thinking
&gt;&gt;&gt; under the radar). Developed a deep appreciation for the power of
&gt;&gt;&gt; metrics. But also learned the dirty little secret of process work,
&gt;&gt;&gt; which is - as soon as there are multiple variations - NOBODY follows
&gt;&gt;&gt; the process.

&gt;&gt;&gt; But, I asked the question - what if this were taken as a given
&gt;&gt;&gt; and not
&gt;&gt;&gt; a problem - that people are always changing the process in a complex
&gt;&gt;&gt; adaptive system? Then how would we map, organize and negotiate the
&gt;&gt;&gt; work? That is when I began looking for a systems mapping method that
&gt;&gt;&gt; would show processes - as a way to quickly bring coherence to the
&gt;&gt;&gt; complex activities we were addressing and also to develop a codified
&gt;&gt;&gt; question set for qualitative interviews for benchmarking.

&gt;&gt;&gt; Virtually anything that looked like a value creation of systems
&gt;&gt;&gt; mapping method became part of my experimentation: interrelationship
&gt;&gt;&gt; diagrams, object oriented data analysis, social network analysis,
&gt;&gt;&gt; context diagramming from software engineering, value added, value
&gt;&gt;&gt; streams - you name it. Over several months of experimentation I put
&gt;&gt;&gt; together the basic HoloMapping(tm) methodology, introduced color
&gt;&gt;&gt; coding, developed the analysis tables and got to work in the real
&gt;&gt;&gt; laboratory of projects.

&gt;&gt;&gt; 1993 First public workshop in the method in San Mateo, California

&gt;&gt;&gt; 1995 First major conference presentation at the National
&gt;&gt;&gt; organization
&gt;&gt;&gt; Development conference in Seattle.

&gt;&gt;&gt; 1997 Worked with Don Tapscott and his group on the research that
&gt;&gt;&gt; eventually became the book Digital Capital (2000). Refined the
&gt;&gt;&gt; method
&gt;&gt;&gt; to include the value conversion dynamics and linkages with
&gt;&gt;&gt; intellectual capital and sustainability. First public
&gt;&gt;&gt; presentation of
&gt;&gt;&gt; new version in Israel. First articles published.

&gt;&gt;&gt; 1998-1999 Authored cover article HR Monthly Australia on Human
&gt;&gt;&gt; Capital
&gt;&gt;&gt; and Value Creation in the Knowledge Economy. Published articles in
&gt;&gt;&gt; Perspectives, 2000 Handbook of Business Strategy. Worked with
&gt;&gt;&gt; Brookings Institution task force on intangibles.

&gt;&gt;&gt; 2000 Published in Journal of Intellectual Capital and Journal of
&gt;&gt;&gt; Business Strategy. Launched the first web-based toolkit and
&gt;&gt;&gt; application with Konvergeandknow, sponsored by Charles Armstrong,
&gt;&gt;&gt; CEO
&gt;&gt;&gt; of one of the top 50 companies in Canada.

&gt;&gt;&gt; 2001 went open source with the methodology on my website and in
&gt;&gt;&gt; public
&gt;&gt;&gt; presentations and workshops.

&gt;&gt;&gt; 2002 presented the full methodology at Transparent Enterprise in
&gt;&gt;&gt; Madrid for validation with the intangibles community. Began offering
&gt;&gt;&gt; qualifications led by Oliver Schwabe, and expanded work to companies
&gt;&gt;&gt; and practitioners in Europe, South Africa, Canada, New Zealand,
&gt;&gt;&gt; Australia and Asia

&gt;&gt;&gt; 2003 published The Future of Knowledge: Increasing Transparency
&gt;&gt;&gt; through Value networks. Cover interviews with Inside Knowledge and
&gt;&gt;&gt; Knowledge Management.

&gt;&gt;&gt; 2004 Began working on value network issues on special projects with
&gt;&gt;&gt; the European Commission and expanded global customer base. Launched
&gt;&gt;&gt; ValueNet Works(tm) practitioner community.

&gt;&gt;&gt; 2005 Developed improved web-based fieldbook and open source
&gt;&gt;&gt; application with Oliver Schwabe. Became a sponsor of the Value
&gt;&gt;&gt; Networks Consortium to help lead standards development and value
&gt;&gt;&gt; network industry development. Expanded usage with US customers
&gt;&gt;&gt; such as
&gt;&gt;&gt; Cisco and Boeing.

&gt;&gt;&gt; 2006-2007 - Too much too tell!

&gt;&gt;&gt; That is a very short version of where the value network analysis
&gt;&gt;&gt; method came from. I have been incredibly fortunate along the way to
&gt;&gt;&gt; have had support, encouragement and excellent suggestions from key
&gt;&gt;&gt; thought leaders and practitioners in new business thinking from many
&gt;&gt;&gt; different disciplines and different parts of the world, some of who
&gt;&gt;&gt; have shown up in this converstion and many others who haven't. As
&gt;&gt;&gt; Oliver likes to say, we have been building on the shoulders of
&gt;&gt;&gt; giants.
&gt;&gt;&gt; We try to truly honor and respect all the good work that goes on in
