Considering that I wrote that at 2:00 in the morning after several
hours of slogging through a complex analysis and report writing it
would appear risky to this non-philosopher to dive into the murky
waters of defending it as a statement of philosophy. But if you
promise not to pulverize me too badly in the process then, yes, I
think I would like to try to defend the statement.

It was not really a casual throwaway, although it may be quite
possible that I will rather botch the task of defending it, since I am
not as well versed in philosophy or as practiced at that kind of
discourse as you are. But there is actually a fairly strong position
behind it that comes from a frustration with the way people use terms
such as &quot;objective&quot; and &quot;subjective&quot; - or &quot;hard&quot; and &quot;soft&quot; which are
the terms used more often in business. My statement was sparked by
Richard's response, where he was weighing what appeared to him to be
two polarities of &quot;hard&quot; and &quot;soft&quot; methodologies.

One of the reasons I enjoy working with performance indicators,
identified value and perceived value is because they so quickly reveal
the true mental models and assumptions that are at play in an
organization. The &quot;hard&quot; numbers are used to reinforce a point of view
or set of beliefs about how the organization should work. Not
surprisingly they can tend to become self fulfiling prophecies, as
almost any measure used in human systems tends to change the human
system it is trying to measure. Or they are based on a set of poor
assumptions and lead to unintended consequences up to and including
complete ruin of the company. People who love &quot;hard&quot; numbers can fall
into Enron type errors or fail to invest in the intangible assets that
build sustainable competitive advantage. We have all seen this.

Let's take the example of &quot;value,&quot; since that is relevant to this
discussion board. People tend to think of financial value as &quot;real&quot; or
&quot;tangible&quot; value, while non-financial value is &quot;soft&quot; or &quot;intangible.&quot;
This distinction is made because non-financial value appears to be
more open to interpretation and people have to perceive that something
has value. (Which is why we work with perceived value in VNA).
However, financial instruments also only have perceived value and have
no value in an of themselves. These are social constructs that allow
us to all get along and get things done more expeditiously without
tediously bartering for every loaf of bread we put in our shopping
carts. Financial systems can collapse virtually overnight and the
instruments become worthless - if the perception of value changes.
Since financial value can be expressed in commonly accepted currencies
it creates an illusion that financial value is somehow more &quot;stable&quot;
or &quot;objective&quot; than non-financial value. Just the fact that financial
instruments have broad acceptance and support does not mean they
represent objective value.

I hope this example helps put some ground under the stand I am taking.
We have of course also many examples through history of how even
scientific reasoning and 'evidence&quot; can be subverted to support the
prevailing world view of a society or culture. When our worldview
begins to change our sciences and the &quot;hard&quot; evidence they produce
begin to change as well. Which comes first the belief that something
might be true or the &quot;evidence&quot; that something is true? We look for
the evidence to support our beliefs, which I believe even die hard
pragmatists would have to agree are fundamentally subjective.

A couple of other things popped into my mind as I was writing this.
Once is a Zen koan I really love: &quot;whatever you say a thing is, it is&quot;
and it's corollary &quot;whatever you say a thing isn't, it isn't.&quot;

The other is how Glenda at Boeing introduces VNA by telling a story of
how Picasso was in conversation with a man who insisted that Picasso
should do paintings that show how things really are. When Picasso said
he didn't understand what he was talking about the man pulled out a
photo of his wife and handed it to him. He said, &quot;Like this - this is
how my wife really is.&quot; Picasso looked at the photograph carefully,
turning it different ways and said, &quot;She's rather small isn't she?
And...rather flat.&quot;

So I may have thoroughly talked myself in circles (won't be the first
time) but it is the best I can do before breakfast with five hours of
sleep.  Nonetheless, Dave, as one who appreciates that the power of
narrative often reveals hidden influencers of meaning and
interpretation even in the most &quot;obvious&quot; of situations, I would think
that, if that statement is indeed post modernism, that there might be
a sympathetic resonance with some of your own thinking?

Cheers,
Verna

