The last thing a conversation is about should be pulverizing and I sincerely
hope by raising a question that this is not where this goes or is
experienced. I really like and respect the VNA stuff. It is just the
question I have about how much it is a circumscribed view of context. In
reality, I have the same question about narrative capture as well.

Just so that my question is not mis understood or misconstrued, here is a
short extract of a piece I am writing with Bill Hall and Luke Naismith (in
press). I am not trying to make a point with this, just to highlight where
the origins of my quandaries about the underlying ontology of
role-link-exchange fits in dealing with the network-hierarchy interface etc.
Bill Hall et al has done much to raise the issue of the &quot;time value of
knowledge&quot; which is what this question is based on (and what our joint paper
points towards). The notion of value here is about adaptation to the
environment and not about $.

Richard

The notion of living organizations

McKelvey (1997, 2002, etc.) argues that organisation science has a very low
status because of the multitude of paradigms it accepts:

...[O]rganisation science is destined to proliferate even more paradigms and
sink to even lower status-surely an unattractive outcome. Campbellian
realism [closely related to Popperian critical scientific realism
(Niiniluoto 1999)] provides a way out of this downward spiral. A dynamic
objectivist organisation science that does not deny social constructionist
sociology of knowledge is possible.

Donald T. Campbell (1960, 1974, 1990, 1990a), coined the term evolutionary
epistemology (EE) in 1974. As it happened quite independently, Karl Popper's
epistemology of evolution covered the same ground with more philosophical
depth and Campbell credits Popper with originating EE and with expressing
this fundamental perspective as early as Logik der Forschung (1934). Both
Campbell and Popper argued that knowledge is an emergent property of life as
it adapts to the world.

