OK, I gave you a choice, but I have no intention of pulverising, so I
will make some statements, ask some questions and add some comments
for you to react to.  To swap excuses, I am writing this in a lodge
in the Yosemite National Park on holiday at the end of a long day in
the heat ....

So rather than attack post modernism per se I thought it would be
better to ask some questions within the Socratic tradition ....

Some questions

1 - Do you think that evolution is just a theory?  It can not be
objectively proved, so other theories (creationism) are equally valid?

2 - The famous case here is a North American Tribe whose creation
myths state that the human race were born from shells in North
America (I may have the details wrong here but the essence is
there).  We can through genetic and other records reasonably well
establish that said tribe migrated to North America from Siberia.
Are both world views equally valid?

3 - Can we objectively establish that something is right or wrong?

Some statements

1 - As a general statement I think its very important for those of us
the involved in narrative &amp; networks to avoid  post-modernism and the
inevitable relativism that goes with that position.  David Boje
probably represents the exemplar of what can go wrong in this case
with concepts of truth and validation going out of the window.  On
tactical grounds (before we get on to its validity or otherwise)
taking such a position will weaken adoption.

2 - Post-modernism is a reaction to modernism, a rejection of the
objectivity of a certain type of science and a recognition of the
ideological nature in which science (and others) have used power.
The science rejected is (for want of a better label) empirical or
Newtonian Science and the concepts of prove and validity contained
within that science is itself limited.  Several of us working in this
field see complex adaptive systems theory as providing a mechanism
for a synthesis of modernism and post-modernism.

3 - Your various statements about hard and soft measures does not
require you to take a post-modernism position, neither does
aesthetics (your Picasso point).  We can establish a fair amount
about the way the brain handles aesthetics, the critically of
metaphor etc. in our evolutionary development of language and
evolution of humans in general.

4 - As you know, my own view is that quantitative methods have
greater intrinsic validity that qualitative ones, but that we can
obtain quantitative material from narrative and other sources.  I
think as this work grows some of the hard/soft issues will go away.
However (to return to a frequent theme) any method which relies on
the qualitative input of material, where those producing the material
are aware of the consequences, have little or no validity other than
for disclosure

It's worth reading &quot;fear of knowledge: against relativism and
constructivism&quot; by Paul Boghossian Prof. of Philosophy at New York
University by the way

