David: OK, I gave you a choice, but I have no intention of
pulverising, so I
will make some statements, ask some questions and add some comments
for you to react to.  To swap excuses, I am writing this in a lodge in
the Yosemite National Park on holiday at the end of a long day in the
heat ....

Verna:   Oh.....I am sooo envious. That is an incredible place
although a bit crowded in August.

David:   So rather than attack post modernism per se I thought it
would be
better to ask some questions within the Socratic tradition ....
Some questions
1 - Do you think that evolution is just a theory?  It can not be
objectively proved, so other theories (creationism) are equally
valid?

Verna:     When does something stop being a theory a become fact? What
exactly does objectively proven mean? Do you mean proven with the
proofs of science (experimentation, research and evidence based),
proven with the proofs of logic or philosophy (coherence), proven by
shared experience or authority? There is probably a continuum of proof
that ranges from the indisputable fact that a dog does indeed have
four legs under normal circumstances, through proving the robustness
of an argument through exploration of its logical coherence, to
validation of belief systems through respected authorities, such as
spiritual teachers.

So no, not all theories are equally valid. Some are supported by
evidence, others are refuted by evidence and others for various
reasons cannot be proven one way or another. If evolution is the
theory that species adapt to their environment, then it is pretty hard
to argue with the scientific evidence and numerous experiments that
this does indeed happen. Creationism can only be proven by spiritual
authority, which in my view makes it a less persuasive theory. I also
believe the claim falls into the trap of mistaking parable and story
as historical fact. Just because historical facts may be woven into a
story does not make it history (to paraphrase Abe Lincoln)

David: &gt;&gt;2 - The famous case here is a North American Tribe whose
creation
myths state that the human race were born from shells in North
America (I may have the details wrong here but the essence is
there).  We can through genetic and other records reasonably well
establish that said tribe migrated to North America from Siberia.
Are both world views equally valid?

Verna:    See above. Also, the validity or &quot;truth&quot; of a mythology or
story such a creation myth is not so much about whether it is true in
fact, but rather if it rings true in the sense of the metaphor or
principle that is the heart of the story. So the question is not
whether both are equally true, but whether both convey verifiable
truths? So a creation myth can be historically untrue, yet be
spiritually or metaphorically true. When stories that are intended as
teaching parables are taken as being historically true religion can
turn ugly.

David:  &gt;&gt;3 - Can we objectively establish that something is right or
wrong?

Verna:      Define objective proof please.

Some statements

David: 1 - As a general statement I think its very important for those
of us
the involved in narrative &amp; networks to avoid  post-modernism and
the
inevitable relativism that goes with that position.  David Boje
probably represents the exemplar of what can go wrong in this case
with concepts of truth and validation going out of the window.  On
tactical grounds (before we get on to its validity or otherwise)
taking such a position will weaken adoption.

Verna: If that is what it is about then I would not put myself in that
bucket.

David: 2 - Post-modernism is a reaction to modernism, a rejection of
the
objectivity of a certain type of science and a recognition of the
ideological nature in which science (and others) have used power.
The science rejected is (for want of a better label) empirical or
Newtonian Science and the concepts of prove and validity contained
within that science is itself limited.  Several of us working in
this
field see complex adaptive systems theory as providing a mechanism
for a synthesis of modernism and post-modernism.

Verna: I do not reject empirical science at all and I would also agree
that the concepts of proof and validity contained within that science
are limited. My argument is that we need to understand the different
approachs to proof and validity and not apply them to questions they
were never designed to address.

David: 3 - Your various statements about hard and soft measures does
not
require you to take a post-modernism position, neither does
aesthetics (your Picasso point).  We can establish a fair amount
about the way the brain handles aesthetics, the critically of
metaphor etc. in our evolutionary development of language and
evolution of humans in general.

Verna: Oh, good.

David: 4 - As you know, my own view is that quantitative methods
have
greater intrinsic validity that qualitative ones, but that we can
obtain quantitative material from narrative and other sources.  I
think as this work grows some of the hard/soft issues will go away.
However (to return to a frequent theme) any method which relies on
the qualitative input of material, where those producing the
material
are aware of the consequences, have little or no validity other
than
for disclosure

Verna: We are in agreement on both points. I would note though that
the value of such disclosure is frequently dismissed when it should
not be. It is a valuable first step toward collective sense making
that allows us to more fully understand another's view as well as our
own, to explore those views and together reach a shared understanding
that allows us to take collective action ina coherent and effective
way. It does not have to plunge us into the messy world of relativism
and all that nonsense about &quot;my truth&quot; and 'your truth&quot; but can
through thoughtful discourse allow us to explore different facets of a
situation and hopefully make better decisions. Better in the sense of
helping us make decisions that support the health and vitality of the
whole. However sense making is not the same as doing empirical science
although empirical science can great enhance the quality of sense
making.

David: It's worth reading &quot;fear of knowledge: against relativism
and
constructivism&quot; by Paul Boghossian Prof. of Philosophy at New York
University by the way

Verna: Intriguing title. Sounds like fun. Are there Cliff Notes? (Just
kidding.)

Happy hiking...
Verna

